<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1148]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis box="[199,335,1015,1040]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1015,1040]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Comments</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The head of each of the available specimens is tilted down, thus emphasising the length of the mouth cone such that this reaches just beyond the fore coxae. The species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1925" box="[1210,1342,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Physothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hargreavesi">
<emphasis box="[1210,1342,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">hargreavesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but has much shorter setae on the head and pronotum, and antennal segments III and IV have slightly less prolonged apices (
<figureCitation box="[159,245,1124,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,337,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-115@5.[151,1436,337,1923]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Craspedothrips species. C. hargreavesi 8–12: (8) pro, meso and metanota, and tergites I–II; (9) tergites VII–IX; (10) sternites V–VII; (11) male head and antennae; (12) female antenna. C. malaysiae antennal segments I–V 13–14: (13) paratype from Bali; (14) holotype." pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Figs 12</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[257,288,1124,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–28" captionStartId="8.[151,263,1754,1777]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,157,1731]" captionTargetId="figure-135@8.[151,1436,157,1743]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22–28. Craspedothrips species. C. nyanzai 22–23: (22) pro, meso and metanota, and tergites I–II; (23) antenna. C. poecilus 24–25: (24) pro, meso and metanota, and tergites I–II; (25) tergites V–IX. C. reticulatus 26–28: (26) head and thorax; (27) tergites I–V; (28) sternites V–VII." pageId="9" pageNumber="58">23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
